{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170963/1937121601/0699.xml":{"full_text":"FINANCIAL NEWS\nThe Business Trend\nRecession Less Rapid\nHopes tor steadier commodity prices\nas a possible turning point in the\nrecession have not yet received\nstatistical verification. Copper, a sign\nificant factor in world commodity\nmarkets, did not hold to its level ot\nthe previous week. The Annalist's\nindex as of Tuesday (it is to carry\nWednesday quotations hereafter),\nshowed the loss of nearly a point for\ntrie week, after a fractional rise the\nweek before. But this decline was\ncaused largely by declines in livestock,\nwhich were not offset by the gains in\nmany industrial commodities. And\ncotton prices.\neven advancing after the government\nestimate ot'a crop ot 18,T4S,v\u2019M bales\nwas published.\nThere was. consequently, no reason\nto depart from the view that a steady\ning ot commodity prices in raw ma\nterials and some manufactured goods\nis a possibility of the near future. In\nfact, the New York Times said on\nFriday: 'The resistance of commodity\nprices to further price declines is con\nsidered encouraging in many sections\nof the financial community, which be\nlieve that it may mean that the cur\nrent business recession is nearing its\nbottom.\" The Times points out that\ncommodities not affected by the pend\ning farm legislation have recently\nshowed moderate strength.\nA few advances in steel scrap prices\nhave been recorded, and in most\nmarkets the declines have been\nchecked. The Iron Age regards this\nas the most important developpient in\nthe steel industry. The scrap market,\nthat journal says, is \"beginning to\nreflect signs of a turn in the steel\nsituation which may not be fully ap\nparent until the December inventory\nperiod is past.\u201d The magazine. Steel,\nsays today that a distinct change in\nsentiment has taken place.\nIn the cotton goods market heavier\npurchases of gray cloth, which is con\nsidered a rood barometer, were\nsufficient one day last week to cause\na slight advance in the price. While\nthis move was precipitated by an\nnouncements of a further curtailment\nin cotton goods production that cur\ntailment will hasten the day when\ncotton goods will again have to be\nproduced in accordance with current\ndemand.\nStable prices and the depletion of\ndealers' stocks are the necessary con\nditions for a revival in various in\ndustries. The steel industry is not an\nexception so far as consumer's needs\nare concerned, but it is troubled by\nhigh costs of operation, the weak de\nmand for capital goods, including con\nstruction requirements, and the pros\npect of a diminished output in the\nautomobile industry. The automobile\noutlook Is not now considered hopeful,\nand it is feared that production of new\ncars and trucks in the first quarter\nof 1938 will be the lowest since 1934.\nNot an \u2022\u2018Assumption\u201d\nOn the basis of actual figures and\nnormal December comparisons the\nbusiness recession is still increasing,\nbut at a slower rate. During the week\nPresident Roosevelt was quoted as\nremarking that the business recession\nwas \"an assumption.\u201d What he meant\nwas that current intensification of the\nrecession was an assumption. Inas\nmuch as his message to Congress\ndefinitely recognized the recession,\nthere was no reason to suppose that\nhe had actually questioned the reality\nof the recession. His remark was mis\nunderstood.\nThis is a matter in which business\nindexes afford the most reliable evi\ndence of current operations and\nauthentic trade and price reports give\nthe best clews as to the future. The\ngovernment already possesses an au\nthoritative agency for digesting com\nmodity prices. The Federal Reserve\nsystems report of department store\nsales Is trustworthy but less scientific,\nif. indeed, a scientific reporting of\nsales is possible without cumbersome\ndetails. During the week Secretary\nof the Treasury Morgenthau asked for\na record of retail sales from key stores\nthroughout the country, but no special\nreason for his request was known.\nThe weekly reports from various in\ndustries are highly valuable, but there\nis no satisfactory general weekly re\nport of wholesale and retail trade.\nIn discussion and exhortation on\nrecovery themes the week was prolific,\nand the Wall Street Journal spoke of\n\"a hurricane of speeches sweeping\nover the eastern seaboard.\" They were\nnot. perhaps, as searching in comment\nand analysis as less conspicuous\nspeeches made the week before. But\nthe meeting of the National Assciation\nof Manufacturers produced some\nspecific ideas as well as a good many\navowals of hope, policy and intention,\nand no one expresses any dissent from\nthe counsels both of individual initia\ntive and of cooperation with govern\nment agencies.\nRailroad Problem\nThe railroads were brought sharply\nto public attention by President\nRoosevelt\u2019s remarks at a press con\nference on Friday. The President was\nreported as saying that he had every\nhope that the Interstate Commerce\ncommission would work out a plan by\nwhich, with consolidations, abandon\nment of uneconomic Unes and read\njustment of capital organizations, the\nroads might be restored to solvency.\nPresident Roosevelt did not favor gov\nernment subsidy, but it is considered\nprobable that the RFC will assist car\nriers which may need temporary\nfinancial aid.\nThe Presidents views embrace a\nlong-range look and are probably in\naccord with the views of most private\nstudents of railway finance. Concern\nmay perhaps be felt as to the extent\nto which granting of rate advances in\nthe current proceedings may be made\nconditional on consolidations or co\nordinated operation.\nIt Is evident that relief will he\nneeded before consolidations or even\nany extended program of coordination\ncan be put Into effect. For one thing,\ncoordination is going to mean loss of\njobs for many employes, and resist\nance will come from that quarter.\nMoreover, coordination will be unsatis\nfactory if it Involves the relinquish\nment of lines or facilities for which\nneed may arise In the future. And\nthere Is the further difficulty that\nbonds are secured by Hens on partic\nular facilities.\nSo far as is known the railroads\nhave intended to make no general\ncurtailment of forces until the pending\nrate case is settled. But the loss of\ntraffic due to the recession makes the\nsituation more critical. Already, of\ncoune. operating employes In freight\nU. S. STEEL TAKES\nLAST STEP TOWARD\nREVAMPED SETUP\nAnnounces Formation of\nDelaware Management\nConcern, Capping Decade\nof Corporate Changes\nNew York. Dec. S\u2014(AP)\u2014The last\nstep in a decade-long revamping of\nthe corporate setup ot the nation's\nioeei giant, U. S. Steel eorpor ta,\nwas apnounced today Io a move which\nwill\" concentrate management ot the\nproperties in a new concern at Pitts\nburg. The action leaves only the fi\nnancial and policy-making functions\nto be directed from historic \"71 Broad\nway.\u201d in New York's Wall street dis\ntrict.\nMyron C. Taylor, who next April is\nto leave the helm as chairman ot\nUnited States Steel, revealed formation\nof a management concern. United\nStates Steel corporation ot Delaware,\nall of whose stock will be owned by\nthe parent. United States Steel corpor\nation ot New Jersey, to manage and\ncoordinate under contract, most ot\nthe principal subsidiaries' activities.\nBenjamin Fairless, now president of\nCarnegie Illinois Steel corporation, and\nto become president of \"big steel\" the\nfirst of the year, will head the man\nagement group as president. Other\nofficers will be chosen tomorrow. Di\nrectors are mostly presidents ot the\nsubsidiaries which will be managed\nby the Delaware corporation.\nA part of Taylor\u2019s statement, \u201cwith\nnew appointments to high executive\npositions,\" led some persons in steel\ncircles to think the personnel of the\nPittsburg group might contain some\nsurprises in the form of new or rel\natively little known steel men named\nto top berths.\n\u201cCapstone of Taylor\u2019s Career\u201d\nIn Wall street the corporate shake\nup was seen as in a sense the cap\nstone of Myron Taylor's career in\nsteel. The steel-maker, who came\nto his present job through the law.\nhad largely conceived, and it is now\nconceded, brought to realty a gigan\ntic plan for the simplification and\nmodernization of the steel colossus\nwhich has been 10 years in the mak\ning. It included retirement of more\nthan $150,000,000 of bonds, leaving\nno funded debt.\nHe is known to have envisaged a\nsimpler and more modern \"big steel\u201d\nsince the day he became chairman of\nthe finance committee in 1927. He\nsaid today \"We began study ot this\nplan (the management concern) in\none form or another in 1929, and in\nits broad aspects it was agreed on\nby the board of directors in 1932.\u201d\nThat he himself saw its completion\nas perhaps the final milestone for\nhim in steel appeared likely in view\not his statement today:\u2014\n\u201cThis plan, when made effective,\nwill conclude the several major basic\nfactors in the plans for the readjust\nment of the corporation's principal\naffairs for the present.\u201d\nMONTH LOW HIT\nBY INDUSTRY, SAYS\nFEDERAL RESERVE\nBulletin Traces Causes of\nDecline Since Spring,\nFinds Bank Credit Ample\nfor New Recovery\nWashington. Dec. 12\u2014(API \u2014Indus-\ntrial production declined in November\nI to the lowest point in 20 months, the\nFederal Reserve board announced to\nday.\nThe hoard made a preliminary es\ntimate that production last month fell\ni to 95 per cent of the 1923-25 average.\nThis compared with 103 in October,\n111 in September and an average of\n115 for the first eight months of the\nyear.\nThe board's monthly bulletin traced\nthe course of this recession, which it\nattributed to maladjustments in costs,\nprices and speculative buying. Early\nthis year, the board related, husiness\ni men thought the trend of rising costs\nand prices then in sharp evidence\nwould continue. They themselvesac\ncentuated abnormal increases by\nstocking up beyond immediate needs\nI in the hope of avoiding higher prices\nlater.\nPrice Decline Aggravated\nI By April, the board continued, it\nI became ciear the rise had been over\ndone, whereupon speculative buying\ni stopped. Production leveled off and\nwhen the possibility of price decreases\nappeared, businessmen delayed pur\nchases in the expectation of saving.\nJust as advance buying against pros\npective price rises accentuated the\nrises and stimulated production, so\nthe new movement to curtail inven\ntories in preparation for lower prices\naggravated price declines and slowed\nI production.\nThroughout the summer the im\nmediate future of business depended\non a race to dispose of surplus inven\ntories before factories exhausted un\nfilled orders on hand. But the fac\ntories lost, and finally in September\nthey had to curtail production. About\nthe same time the stock market suf\nfered its first serious sinking spells\nand called general attention to the\nsituation.\nThe board made no predictions, but\nnoted, that the supply of bank credit\nIs ample to finance a new recovery.\nAlthough demand deposits have de\nclined \u00bb<r>o.ooo.ooo during the year,\nreal savings of the people and busl\nness Increased as shown by a |530,-\n000.000 gain in time deposits.\nLONDONSILVERPACT\nWON\u2019T BE RENEWED\nWashington. Dec. 13\u2014(API\u2014An in\nformed government official said today\nthe London silver stabilization treaty,\nwhich expires January 1. would not\nbe renewed.\nThe treaty, signed tour years ago\nby the United States, China. India.\nSpain. Australia, Canada, Mexico, and\nPeru, pledged those nations to bolster\nsilver prices by keeping large quan\ntities of silver off of the market.\nThe United States, for Instance\npromised to buy at least 24.421.410\nounces annually and has more than\nfulfilled Its quota. Despite such com\npliance the treaty generally has been\nconsidered a failure.\nservice have been dropped because\nthere was no freight for them to\nhandle. Freight car loadings in the\ncountry as a whole were 15.4 per cent\nlower than a year ago for the last\nweek reported.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN; SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, DECEMBER 16, 1937\nStock Exchange Moves\nTo Clean Its Own House\nAlso Will Consider Higher Commissions\u2014President\nGay to Name Group to Study Sweeping Adminis\ntrative Changes\nNew York, Dec. B\u2014(AP)\u2014Respond\ning to \u201creform\u201d pressure from Wash\nington, and the economic pressure of\nmembers\u2019 dwindling revenues, the gov\nerning committee of the New York\nStock exchange moved today to con\nsider sweeping changes in administra\ntion and an Increase in commissions.\nCharles R. Gay, president, was au\nthorized to appoint a committee of\nnine to study \"all aspects of a further\ndevelopment of the organization and\nadministration of the exchange.\"\nOatathston Jnrraase Urged\nAt the same time, the povernlzi?\ncommittee received a report from the\ncommittee on quotations and commis\nsions proposing an increase in com\nmissions\u2014the amount which members\ncharge for buying and selling securi\nties for customers \u2014up to 11 per cent.\nIt was announced this would be con\nsidered at a special meeting on the\n15th, together with a proposed amend\nment making the maximum increases\n18 per cent.\nThat sweeping changes in stock ex\nchange administration were under con\nsideration came to light November 23,\nwhen William O. Douglas, chairman\nof the Securities and Exchange com\nmission, called upon stock exchanges\nto clean house or face drastic federal\nregulation. Douglas proposed particu\nlarly that the exchange be adminis\ntered by a salaried expert, executive\npersonnel, rather than by member\ncommittees.\nLeaders Said Insisted Upon\nGay gave no indication as to whom\nhe would select for the committee au-\nRAILROAD INCOME\nMUST BE BOOSTED\nR.F.C. HEAD STATES\nEither That or Roads Will\nHave to Be Subsidized by\nGovernment, Says Chair\nman Jess Jones\nWashington, Dec. B\u2014(AP)\u2014Rail\nroad revenues must be increased or\nthe roads must be subsidized by the\ngovernment. Chairman Jesse H.\nJones of the RFC said today after\ndiscussing the plight of the carriers\nwith President Roosevelt.\nHe said he told the chief executive\nthat the lines were in poor financial\ncondition and that they had made out\na strong case for increased freight\nrates during current proceedings be\nfore the I. C. C. The RFC, he added,\nstands ready to help by extending its\npresent loans to the roads whenever\nsuch help is required. He said it is\nfortunate that the carriers have no\nextensive obligations maturing until\nnext fall.\nThe Jones conference was one of\nseveral at which Mr Roosevelt went\ninto various aspects of the business\nrecession. He discussed unemploy\nment and relief with Harry Hopkins,\nthe head of the Works Progress ad\nministration, the budget with Secre\ntary Morgenthau, and undisclosed\nmatters with Donald Richberg of the\nold NRA and De Lancey Kountze, a\nNew York manufacturer.\nMeanwhile, Chairman Eccles of the\nFederal Reserve board attributed the\nnew depression to \u201cunbalanced prices\u201d\nand said that a prolongation of the\nslump would prevent a balanced\nbudget. He told the Senate banking\ncommittee that farm prices are too\nlow. as compared with the prices of\nbasic industrial materials such as\nsteel, and the income of farmers, un\norganized workers and government\nemployes is too low as compared with\nthe incomes of other groups.\nThe slowness with which one group\nof prices goes up. or the other goes\ndown, \"will determine the extent of\nthis depression.\u201d he testified. On the\nbrighter side of the business, he said,\nwas the fact that the stock market\nhas advanced without the expansion\nof credit which accompanied the boom\nof 1929. and that the present reces\nsion has seen no forced liquidation\nsuch as occurred in 1929.\nMr Jones\u2019s conference with the\nPresident recalled that methods of\nenabling the railroads to increase\ntheir purchases of equipment, to the\nbenefit of the heavy industries, have\nbeen under consideration for some\ntime.\nDiversity of Snb.leets\nHopkins, who lunched with the\nPresident, said they talked of \u201cun\nemployment, relief, and fishing.\u201d He\nadded that on the first two subjects\nthe discussion went exhaustively into\nall phases of the problems presented.\nMorgenthau, as usual, said nothing\nabout his meeting with the executive.\nThis being the budget making season\nof the year, it was taken for granted\nthat that subject was discussed.\nIn that connection, members of the\nHouse who have seen portions of the\nbudget estimates for the next fiscal\nyear reported that for five depart\nments on the independent offices an\nincrease in administrative expenses Is\nbeing considered.\nA decrease In overall totals for\nthese agencies however is In prospect,\nthey said. The decrease Is being\nachieved, they explained, by slashing\nthe amounts allotted to expenses\nwhich are expected to occur In the\nnext fiscal year only *nd not be re\nported In the years following.\nWashington. Dec. 8 (AP) \u2014The\nInterstate Commerce commission,\nwhich has listened for a week and a\nhalf to laments of the railroads, heard\ntoday that the sprawling new motor\ntruck industry also is in financial\ndifficulties.\nChester G. Moore, secretary of\nAmerican Trucking Associations. Inc.,\ndeclared that If the railroads get a\nrequested 15 per cent Increase In\nfreight rates, the truckers should re\nceive a similar boost. On the basis\nof this year's business, he figured\nthat a 15 per cent truck rate rise\nwould produce 875.000.000 of new rev\nenue.\nHarry R. Brown, spokesman for the\nthird great group of freight carriers,\nthe Intercoastal ship operators, said\nthe water lines also would demand\nhigher rates. Brown, chairman of\nthe Intercoastal Steamship Freight\nassociation, said they would make\ntheir application before the Mari, .to\ncommission after the railroad re\nquest was settled by the 1. C. C\nMoore declared that because of In\n\u25a0creased material, wage and tax coats\nthe trucking industry\u2019s spread be\ntween Income and expenses had\nreached \"the vanishing point\" and the\nIndustry is \"desperately in need of\nmore revenue.\"\nHe declared that 434 representa\ntive carriers\u2014about Id per cent of\nthe total \u2014had Increased their income\nfrom 891.533,079 In 1935 to 8105.135,-\n551 In 1937 but thst total expenses\nhad tumped from 889,358,458 to $104.-\n761,518.\nthorized, but it was learned from usu\nally well-informed stock exchange\nsources that an Important group among\nthe membership was Insistent upon\nselection of a committee of outstand\ning persons, representing ths public\nand all important elements in the se\ncurities business. They were particu\nlarly insistent, it was said, upon a\ncommittee which would command pub\nlic confidence.\nOne prominent broker said that un\nless the committee selected met these\nrequirements, this socxlM \u201cVhersl'\ng>n>lp within the mp/nbershlp \u2018wou'u\nselect a\"\"rump\u201d committee ot its own.\nThe governing committee's authori\nzation was in the form of the follow\ning resolution:\n\"Resolved, that the president appoint\na committee not to exceed nine per\nsons to consider all aspects of a fur\nther development of the organization\nand administration ot the exchange,\nincluding, among others the advisabili\nty of making the presidency a salaried\noffice, or transferring greater admin\nistrative responsibility to executives,\nand ot making the function ot the\nstanding committees supervisory rath\ner than administrative, and to report\nits recommendations to the governing\ncommittee as promptly as possible;\nand be it further\n\"Resolved, that the committee be\nauthorized to employ such expert as\nsistance as it may deem advisable.\u201d\nAn increase in commissions had been\nI agitated among the membership for\nsome time.\nThe report ot the committee on quo\ntations and commissions proposes a\nminimum commission to be charged\nrhe public of 8$ Instead of the present\n81 minimum, and proposes a minimum\nmonthly service charge of $2 on in\nactive accounts. It is understood that\nat the present time, most member\nfirms are charging the 83 minimum\nfor each transaction.\nCommission rates on transactions\nmade for each other by members ot\nthe exchange would be increased by\napproximately 5 per cent, compared\nwith 11 per cent for nonmembers.\nThe governors of the exchange re\nceived the report without comment or\naction. An unnamed member ot the\ngoverning committee proposed an\namendment to the report, recommend\ning an increase of around 18 per cent\nin nonmember commissions\nThe committee's report, in general,\nprovides for a more graduated in\ncrease in nonmember commission rates,\nstarting at three cents on each 81\nvaluation of a stock, increasing 1 per\ncent per 81 up to 819- and then in\ncreasing 1 cent more for each addi\ntional 810 in price.\nAt present, there is little graduation\nin the scale of commissions. For ex\nample, the commission is the same for\nthe class of stocks priced at 8110 to\n8200 \u201425 cents a share. Under the pro\nposed schedule. It would be 23 cents a\nshare on each 8110. and increase one\ncent per 810 additional in price up to\n32 cents a share for 8200 \u2014allowing a\ngreater return to brokers. Similar\ncomparisons hold true in other price\ngroups.\nCOMPETITION SAID\nHINDERED IN SALE\nOF CARBURETORS\nCarter Corporation Charged\nWith Violating Federal\nLaws by Exclusive Dealer\nContracts\nWashington, Dec. S\u2014(AP) The\nFederal Trade commission announced\ntoday it had issued a complaint\naccusing the Carter Carburetor cor\nporation at St Louis of violating the\nClayton act and the Federal Trade\ncommission act.\nThe Clayton act prohibits exclusive\ndealer contracts the effect of which\nmay be to lessen competition substan\ntially or to tend to create a monopoly,\ni The Federal Trade commission act\nI forbids unfair methods of competition\nI in Interstate commerce.\nThe commission alleged the com\npany supplied more than 50 per cent\nof the carburetors used as original\nequipment on automobiles produced\nthis year. It also accused the com\npany of entering into contracts with\nmore than 900 dealers.\n\"Pursuant to the terms ot the con\ntract,\" the commission announcement\nsaid, \"the dealer receives 50 per cent\ndiscount from the list price on car\nburetor products, as against a 25 per\ncent discount available to the retail\ntrade generally.\"\n\u201cTo Hinder Competition\u201d\nSince April, 1937, the complaint said,\nthe company had maintained a policy\nof refusing to enter Into, renew or\ncontinue sales contracts with, or to\ngrant the preferential discount to\ndealers who sold carburetor products\nmanufactured and marketed by com\npetitors who entered the field after\nJune 23, 1934.\nThe complaint alleged the company\nhad notified all contract holders that\nit would terminate the agreements\nand discontinue the preferential dis\ncount if they sold other than Carter\nproducts. It further alleged that the\ncompany and Its distributors had ter\nminated contracts with some dealers\niefusing to accept the conditions laid\ndown, and that distributors had been\ninstructed to allow* such dealers only\nthe 25 per cent discount.\nThe commission charged that the\n\"tendency and effect of the Carter\ncompany's acts and practices have\nbeen to hinder and lessen competition\nin the sale of carburetor products; to\nobstruct and interfere with the nor\nmal and natural flow ot trade in such\nproducts; to injure those of Its com\npetitors against whom Its policy is\ndirected by unfairly diverting busi\nness and trade from them and to\nprevent a considerable number of\nservice stations from handling and\nselling a full line of carburetors snd\nparts.\u201d\nThe commission asked the company\nto answer the complaint within 20\ndays.\nTRADE WITH JAPAN\nJap Imports from 11, S. Increased\nI\u2019er Cent In t*\nTokio. Dec. 12\u2014(AP)\u2014Japan's Im\nports front the United States were\n55. J per cent greater during the first\n10 months of t9S7 than for the -ame\nperiod In 1936. figures of the com\nmerce ministry showed today. Jap\nanese exports to America rose 20.6\nper cent.\nImports from the United States\ntotalled 6606,575.000 for a 6126.666.000\ngain; exports rose 627,550.000 to\n$165,600,000, leaving Japan with an\nunfavorable trade balance of sl4s,-\n275,000.\nNEW YORK STOCK MARKET\nSale of Stocks\nHew York Stock oxchaage\nSew York Carb exchange 187,000\nBoston Sock exchange 19308\nSTOCK AVERAGES\n(Compiled by the Aetoeiated Preet)\n85 15 15 50\nlad. Relit UtU. Stks.\nSet change +4 one. \u2014.2 +.l\nTuesday *B-5 (Lt MM) 44.7\nPreview day 59.3 IL! 83.2 44.5\nMonth ago 534 2!4 834 40.9\nYear ago 95.5 BS.S 51.7 <O4\n1987 high 101.5 49.5 54.0 754\n1937 low 57.7 194 ALO 41.7\n1985 high 994 484 724\n1980 low 78.4 80.2 43.4 55.7\nMovement Rc-eeat Yes re\nfhfi low 174 8.7 28.9 15.9\nhlrh 1\u00ab.\u00bb 138.9 IM^ 15.7,7\n1927 low 514 M 4 014 514\nNew York, Dec 14\u2014(AP)\u2014The stock\nmarket shifted aimlessly during the\ngreater part of today's session, al\nthough late buying in major steels\nhelped balance the list.\nMore year-end tax selling tended to\nkeep speculative forces in a waiting\nframe of mind, the theory being that\nadjustments for Income returns may\nobstruct any substantial upward push\nover the next two weeks.\nMost traders failed to work up a\nfever over Japanese complications.\nThe belief was generdal in the finan\ncial sector that the affair ot the\nbombed American ships will be set\ntled with apologies and reparations\nfrom Tokio.\nWhile there was a wide assortment\not losers at the close, the Associated\nPress average ot 60 stocks managed\nto emerge .1 ot a point higher at 44,7.\nDealings were, quiet from the start,\ntransfers totaling 896,330 shares com\npared with 1,017,284 yesterday.\nSteels were aided by forecasts of a\nreversal at least after the turn of the\nyear, in the long downward production\ndrift. Mill operations were up at\nYoungstown and only slightly off at\nPittsburg.\nGold mines were given a play with\nHomestake edging into new high\nground for the year.\nMotors continued to lack vitality,\nas did rails, rubbers, utilities and\namusements.\nSentiment was bolstered by remarks\nof Chairman Eccles of the Federal\nReserve bpard regarding dwindling\ninventories and the possibility busi\nnessmen may have to bid against\neach other at advancing prices if they\ndelay necessary purchases too long.\nProminent shares on the upside a\npoint or more included United States\nSteel at s\u00ab\u2019i. Bethlehem 56, Sears\nRoebuck 58^4, Dome Mines 50%.\nAmerican Smelting 47%, American\nCan 75%, General Electric 42%. Stan\ndard Oil of New Jersey 43%, Amer\nican Tobacco B 63% and Owens-\nIllinois 63%.\nLaclede Gas common and preferred\ndropped more than 2 each when the\nMissouri supreme court ruled against\nthe company's plea for a rehearing of\nan order cutting gas rates.\nAmong lesser losers were J. I. Case\nat 91, General Motors 33. Westing\nhouse 104%, American Telephone 145%\nland Montgomery Ward 33.\nWestern Union was off at 24.\nThe concern reported 10 months\u2019 earn\nings equal to 32.82 a share. In the\nI same period last year profits amoun\nted to 35.54 a share.\nI Call money steady; 1 per cent all\nday. Prime commercial paper 1.\nI Time loans steady; 60 to 90 days 1%;\nfour to six months 1%. Bankers\u2019 ac\nceptances unchanged. Rediscount rate.\nNew York Reserve bank, 1 per cent.\nBar silver unchanged at 44% cents\nau ounce.\nFollowing is a complete list of final\nI stock transactions:\nNet\nSales in 100 Hi\u00bbh Low Cloee Chg.\nA\n1 Abbott Lab 37 37 37 1\n7 Adame Exp 9% 9 9%+\n1 Adama-Ml